        {/* Section 5 */}
        <section id="contrarian-angles">
          <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold text-white">5. Contrarian Angles: Standing Out by Challenging Consensus</h2>
          <p className="text-zinc-300 leading-relaxed">Contrarian angles challenge widely accepted beliefs or practices in your industry. They work because they create cognitive dissonance — the reader sees something that contradicts what they believe, and they cannot scroll past without engaging. Contrarian content generates 4.7x more comments and 2.3x more shares than consensus content.</p>
          <p className="text-zinc-300 leading-relaxed">But contrarian does not mean clickbait. The best contrarian angles are backed by genuine insight, personal experience, or data. They are not designed to shock — they are designed to reveal a truth the industry has overlooked.</p>
          <div className="bg-zinc-900 border border-zinc-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 space-y-3">
            <p className="text-zinc-300"><strong className="text-white">Template 1 — Challenge a best practice:</strong> &quot;Why [Commonly Accepted Practice] Is Actually Hurting Your [Metric].&quot; Example: &quot;Why Posting Every Day Is Actually Killing Your Instagram Growth.&quot;</p>
            <p className="text-zinc-300"><strong className="text-white">Template 2 — Reverse the advice:</strong> &quot;Stop [Common Advice]. Do [Opposite] Instead.&quot; Example: &quot;Stop Chasing Followers. Start Building a Waiting List.&quot;</p>
            <p className="text-zinc-300"><strong className="text-white">Template 3 — Expose a myth:</strong> &quot;The [Industry] Lie Nobody Talks About.&quot; Example: &quot;The Engagement Rate Lie: Why Your 5% Rate Is Actually Terrible.&quot;</p>
            <p className="text-zinc-300"><strong className="text-white">Template 4 — Counter-intuitive insight:</strong> &quot;The [Unexpected Thing] That [Surprising Result].&quot; Example: &quot;The Ugliest Thumbnails Get the Most Clicks: A 10,000-Video Study.&quot;</p>
          </div>
          <p className="text-zinc-300 leading-relaxed"><strong className="text-white">The golden rule of contrarian content:</strong> You must be able to back up your contrarian take with evidence, data, or credible experience. Contrarian without substance is just trolling, and audiences see through it instantly. Build your argument before you announce your position.</p>
          <p className="text-zinc-300 leading-relaxed">Contrarian angles work best for brands that have established some baseline authority. If you are brand new, start with data-driven or story-based angles to build credibility, then introduce contrarian takes once your audience trusts your expertise.</p>
          <p className="text-zinc-300 leading-relaxed"><strong className="text-white">Frequency matters:</strong> If every post is contrarian, you become the brand that just disagrees with everything. That is not a strategy, it is a personality disorder. Use contrarian angles for 15-25% of your content mix. The rest should reinforce your core expertise through data, stories, and educational content. The contrarian pieces generate spikes of attention. The other content converts that attention into trust.</p>
          <p className="text-zinc-300 leading-relaxed">Also consider the contrarian spectrum. Not every contrarian take needs to be a radical position reversal. Soft contrarian angles (&quot;This popular strategy works, but not the way most people use it&quot;) are often more effective than hard contrarian angles (&quot;This entire strategy is a lie&quot;) because they invite nuanced discussion rather than defensive reactions.</p>
        </section>

